# EdgeLens working rules

## Product boundary
- EdgeLens is a deterministic, client-side auditor for AI-generated React and shadcn components.
- State completeness is the primary wedge; accessibility risk detection is supporting evidence.
- Do not add a backend, database, LLM call, account system, or uploaded-code storage without an explicit product decision.

## Repository isolation
- Treat this repository as the complete source of truth for EdgeLens.
- Do not read from, import from, or write EdgeLens application code into Headroom, XProductInsights, sherv-website, or another product repository unless Sherv explicitly requests a reviewed migration.
- Never copy credentials, analytics configuration, private screenshots, user-submitted source, or project-management data between products.
- Keep the Cursor workspace single-root. Do not add sibling repositories to `edgelens.code-workspace`.

## Model routing
- Use Grok 4.5 Very Fast for normal implementation, UI work, documentation, and routine debugging.
- Escalate to Sonnet 5 only for difficult architecture or privacy issues, unresolved bugs, or final release QA.

## Privacy and analytics
- User-pasted source code, component names, parse errors, selectors, and rendered report text are sensitive.
- Never send those values to analytics, logs, URLs, query parameters, session replay, or external services.
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` values are public browser configuration and must never contain secrets.
- Recording routes must remain deterministic and excluded from analytics.

## Engineering defaults
- Next.js App Router, React, TypeScript, Tailwind, npm.
- Keep analysis deterministic and explainable.
- Prefer minimal dependencies and narrow changes.
- Before completion run `npm run audit:public`, `npm run typecheck`, `npm run lint`, and `npm run build`.
